{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"0258644d-42c1-4563-8479-545218444eff","content":"In ASP.NET Core, `AddScoped` creates one instance **per HTTP request** — the request is the scope boundary. In MAUI, there's no equivalent request pipeline, so the default scope is the **entire application lifetime**. This means `AddScoped` effectively behaves like `AddSingleton`, and your DbContext (and its change tracker) lives forever.\n\n**Fixes:**\n\n1. **Use `AddTransient<MyDbContext>()`** — new instance each time it's injected.\n2. **Create scopes manually** using `IServiceScopeFactory`:\n   ```csharp\n   using var scope = scopeFactory.CreateScope();\n   var db = scope.ServiceProvider.GetRequiredService<MyDbContext>();\n   ```\n3. **Short-lived contexts** — instantiate `new MyDbContext(options)` directly where needed and dispose after use.\n\nOption 1 is the simplest for most MAUI apps. Option 2 gives you explicit control over the lifetime boundary.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"f7833630-f069-49f4-9103-3feca6518db3","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about a common pitfall when migrating from ASP.NET Core to .NET MAUI regarding dependency injection scoping, specifically with `AddScoped` and DbContext lifetime.\n\nThis is a conceptual question I can answer directly without needing to look at any code or files.\n\nThe key issue: In ASP.NET Core, `AddScoped` creates a new instance per HTTP request (the \"scope\" is the request pipeline). In MAUI, there's no HTTP request pipeline — the default scope is the **application lifetime** itself, meaning `AddScoped` behaves essentially like `AddSingleton`. This causes the DbContext to persist its tracked entities across page navigations.","outputTokens":398,"requestId":"482E:1E3288:9D136B:B88334:69F3FD43"},"id":"fc55daad-5bad-4fba-bb9d-68326ce63220","timestamp":"2026-05-01T01:09:33.379Z","parentId":"c905395c-d807-4c04-89e4-2a016c585575"}
